5 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Enforcement. (1) The attorney general has the authority to investigate
6 and prosecute alleged violations of [sections 1 through 5].
7 (2) (a) When it appears to the attorney general that a person has engaged in, is engaging in, or is
8 about to engage in any act or practice declared to be unlawful by [sections 1 through 5], or when the attorney
9 general believes it to be in the public interest that an investigation should be made to ascertain whether a
10 person in fact has engaged in, is engaging in, or is about to engage in any act or practice declared to be
11 unlawful by [sections 1 through 5], the attorney general may execute in writing a civil investigative demand and
12 serve any person who is believed to have information, documentary material, or physical evidence relevant to
13 the alleged or suspected violation.
14 (b) The demand requires the person to furnish, under oath or otherwise, a written report setting
15 forth the relevant facts and circumstances of which the person has knowledge or to appear and testify, or
16 produce relevant documentary material or physical evidence for examination, at a reasonable time and place as
17 may be stated in the investigative demand.
18 (3) (a) To accomplish the objectives and to carry out the duties prescribed by [sections 1 through
19 5], the attorney general, in addition to other powers conferred by [sections 1 through 5], may issue subpoenas
20 to any person, administer an oath or affirmation to any person, conduct hearings in aid of any investigation or
21 inquiry, prescribe forms, and adopt rules as may be necessary that have the force of law.
22 (b) The powers conferred by this section may not be used to compel any natural person to furnish
23 testimony or evidence that might tend to incriminate the person or subject the person to a penalty or forfeiture.
24 (4) Service of any notice, demand, or subpoena under this section must be made personally within
25 this state, but if this cannot be obtained, substitute service may be made in the manner provided in the Montana
26 Rules of Civil Procedure.
27 (5) (a) If a person fails or refuses to file a statement or to report or obey a subpoena or
28 investigative demand issued by the attorney general, the attorney general may, after notice, apply to the district
